                <li>Cms manager</li>
            </ul>

            <h2>Quick start</h2>

            <h3>Adding new module to admin panel</h3>

            <p>
                HatimeriaAdminBundle has already implemented couple of panels for existing modules. We will use CmsPanel as an example how to add your own.
            </p>
            <p>
                First of all create in Resources/public/js directory of your bundle, a directory where you will develop your panel.<br/>
                In our case we named it 'cms'.<br/>
                Most important file in these directory is CmsPanel.js. Its name is combined of name of directory and word 'panel'.<br/>
                It is very important to name it using same standard.
            </p>
            <script src="https://gist.github.com/2633940.js?file=CmsPanel.js"></script>
            <p>
                As you can see full panel class name is 'HatimeriaAdmin.cms.CmsPanel'.<br/>
                HatimeriaAdmin is namespace which must be defined in extjs.yml file in loader section.
            </p>
            <script src="https://gist.github.com/2633940.js?file=extjs.yml"></script>
            <p>
                HatimeriaAdmin namespace is added by default, but you can add it same way as HatimeriaMonitoring.<br/>
                Value is a path to js resource directory. <br/>
                The final touch is to add newly created panel to admin menu. <br />
                To do that simply add the name of you module in defaults.yml under admin_menu key. <br />
            </p>
            <script src="https://gist.github.com/2633940.js?file=defaults.yml"></script>
            <p>
                From now on when you click on your tab in admin menu your panel will be loaded.
            </p>
        </div>
